                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14147224" author="jvz" created="Thu, 25 Sep 2014 01:27:44 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;It currently is. Close?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14147240" author="garydgregory" created="Thu, 25 Sep 2014 01:49:34 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The class may implement Serializable but having it work is another story. Right it will fail, so the issue should remain open.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14952492" author="jvz" created="Sun, 11 Oct 2015 23:43:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;A ton of classes will have to become serializable for this to truly work. That, or a rather complicated pair of serialization methods.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14952939" author="mikaelstaldal" created="Mon, 12 Oct 2015 11:16:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Why should it be Serializable?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14953308" author="jvz" created="Mon, 12 Oct 2015 16:39:55 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The use case brought up was in Spring applications where Loggers are stored as normal fields instead of static fields. Some beans will get cached by HTTP session logic which requires serialization. In this case, I think a smarter serialization method would make more sense as caching all the underlying configuration and context objects seems to be a lot of data that is easily recovered anytime Log4j2 is restarted.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14966249" author="jvz" created="Wed, 21 Oct 2015 05:15:31 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Fixed in master.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
